[ChapterName "Exercise 6: Bishop activation III"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/kNn68T8l/vBX0SPrA"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/1pq2ppp/p1n1pn2/2p5/3P4/P1P1PN2/4BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.02.04"]
[UTCTime "18:10:24"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In this Nimzo-Indian position, black has given up the bishop pair to speed up development and challenge white's center. Considering both sides' bishops, how can we best activate our pieces? }
1... Rd8! (1... e5?! { Possibly a little rushed. After d5 Rd8, e4! we would have to move our c6 knight. Note that Nxe4?? in that position runs into Qc2 with a double attack on our knights and black is lost.
Nowhere in these variations are we activating our c8 bishop. Can we improve upon this idea? } 2. d5 Rd8?! { The most obvious move fails. } (2... e4!? 3. dxc6 Ng4! { The only way to justify this variation. The knight cannot move without allowing a mate on h2. } 4. h3 exf3 5. hxg4 fxe2 6. Qxe2 Qxc6 $10) 3. e4! Nxe4?? 4. Qc2 $18) (1... b5?! { It is an interesting idea to fianchetto the light squared bishop on b7. However, after a4!, white will be able to punish our lack of development and open up the position for their bishop pair. } 2. a4! Bb7 3. axb5 axb5 4. Rxa8 Rxa8 5. Bxb5 $14) (1... b6?! { This soft move doesn't activate the bishop to its best square. After Bb2 Bb7, dxc5 bxc5, c4 - white's bishop pair is felt on the board. } 2. Bb2 Bb7 3. dxc5 bxc5 4. c4 $16) (1... cxd4? { After cxd4, you've just improved white's position tremendously. } 2. cxd4 $16) (1... Na5!? $14 { An interesting idea to get out of the way for the bishop on c6 and the long diagonal. But this move doesn't place enough pressure on white's center, so white has time for Ne5, a4, Ba3 - all improving moves that are tough to meet. }) 2. Qc2 { Rd8 is a nice improving move, so white is quick to get off the same file as the rook. Now that d5 is stopped for good, what is the true idea behind this move though? } 2... e5 (2... Na5!? $10 { An interesting idea to get out of the way for the bishop on c6 and the long diagonal. But this move doesn't place enough pressure on white's center, so white has time for Ne5, a4, Ba3 - all improving moves that are tough to meet. }) 3. Bb2 { Nice! Placing all of our pawns on dark squares complements our remaining light squared bishop. How can we finally activate this piece? } 3... Bg4 $10 { The bishop on g4 places maximum pressure on white's center. With all this tension in the center, none of white's central pawns can move without leaving behind a weakness. Black has full compensation against white's bishop pair. } (3... e4!? { An equally valid move if your follow-up to Nd2 was Bf5. Bad bishops defend good pawns! } 4. Nd2 Bf5 $10) (3... Be6? $16 { After Ng5 our bishop will have to move again immediately. }) (3... Bf5?? { Oh no my bishop! } 4. Qxf5 $18) *


